#Text=Marco Marziale
#Text=Left : Portrait of a man , by Marco Marziale .
#Text=Right : Allegory with unknown coat of arms .
#Text=( Reverse of the portrait ) . Louvre Museum .
#Text=Supper at Emmaus - Gallerie dell'Accademia
#Text=Marco Marziale was a Venetian painter from , known to have been active from 1492/1493 to 1507 . [ 1 ]

#Text=He was a pupil of Giovanni Bellini , as stated in some of his inscriptions signing works , and was also influenced by Giovanni 's brother Gentile , with possibly some elements of the style of Perugino also .

#Text=From January 1493 ( old Julian calendar ) , when he must have at least completed his training , he was employed by the Republic of Venice as an assistant to Giovanni Bellini on the Great Council Chamber in the Doge 's Palace at a fairly modest salary .
#Text=These paintings were all lost in the great fire of 1574 . [ 2 ]
#Text=In 1493 he joined the confraternity of the Scuola di San Marco .
#Text=In about 1500 he may have moved to Cremona , which Venice had just taken over in 1499 , and which it held until 1509 , when the Duchy of Milan recaptured the city .
#Text=Marziale would no doubt have been unwelcome after this , if he was in the city .

#Text=He is not documented there , but painted two altarpieces for Cremonese churches ; it is possible these were sent from Venice , although the records of the scuola show him as absent from the city in 1505 .
#Text=In 1507 he signed works now in London and Berlin , after which nothing further about him is known .
#Text=Several signed works are known , including the only two large altarpieces , both from churches in Cremona and now in the National Gallery , London . [ 3 ]

#Text=Two versions of the Supper at Emmaus , adapted from a lost work by Giovanni Bellini known from a print , are in the Gemäldegalerie , Berlin and the Gallerie dell'Accademia in Venice , where there is also a Circumcision of Jesus in the Museo Correr , dated 1499 .
#Text=Including unsigned attributed works , there is a probable surviving oeuvre of about a dozen paintings ; [ 1 ]
#Text=apart from the wall-paintings lost in 1574 , much of his painting may be among the large number of pieces assigned to the workshop of Giovanni Bellini .

#Text=A small Adoration of the Magi , formerly in the Virginia Museum of Fine Arts , and only just attributed as an early work of Marziale 's , was sold at Christie 's , New York for $ 98,500 in January 2009 . [ 4 ]

#Text=He was a rather conservative painter , whose works continued to follow compositional formats from the late 15th century , despite his possibly being only a few years older than Giorgione and Titian .
#Text=His main figures stand upright and still in the older Venetian style , already long superseded in Florentine art .
#Text=Although his figures are stiff , even " wooden " , [ 5 ]
#Text=he takes great interest in textiles and decor in his works .
#Text=Both the London altarpieces are set in spaces in front of apses decorated with gold mosaics in the manner of San Marco , Venice , and also of altarpieces by Giovanni Bellini . [ 6 ]

#Text=The Circumcision altarpiece features several donor portraits of the family of Tommaso Raimondi , the lawyer and poet who commissioned the work ; their lavish and fashionable clothes are carefully depicted . [ 7 ]

#Text=In 1872 , the English critic John Ruskin asked a friend in Venice to make a careful drawing of the embroidered table-cloth , probably from Egypt , depicted in the Correr Circumcision , which Ruskin adapted into a pattern for wallpaper which he used in the study of his house Brantwood in the Lake District . [ 8 ]
#Text=In Cremona he influenced , and may have trained , Altobello Melone . [ 9 ]
#Text=Notes
#Text=References
